<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,152,1028]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,512,538,564]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Habitat and Distribution</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" box="[549,796,538,563]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="quesadae">
<emphasis box="[549,796,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Pinnularia quesadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare species on Livingston Island and so far only found together with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" box="[419,633,577,602]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="perlanceolata">
<emphasis box="[419,633,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">P. perlanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" box="[699,1134,577,603]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="borealis" variety="pseudolanceolata">
<emphasis box="[699,838,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">P. borealis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[907,1134,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">pseudolanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above) in a large, circumneutral (pH 7.3) shallow pool on Byers Peninsula surrounded by fellfields and moss vegetations, growing into the water.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="48" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,152,1028]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,693,719]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Etymology</emphasis>
:—Named for Prof. Dr. Antonio Quesada (Universidad Autónoma de 
<collectingRegion box="[1194,1285,693,719]" country="Spain" name="Madrid" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Madrid</collectingRegion>
), one of the leading scientists in the Byers Peninsula research and one of the principal investigators of the Limnopolar project on this Peninsula.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,152,1028]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,364,808,834]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Observations</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" box="[402,648,809,834]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="quesadae">
<emphasis box="[402,648,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Pinnularia quesadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is at present the only member of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1093,1204,809,834]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="section" section="Distantes">
<emphasis box="[1093,1204,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Distantes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group with a raphe located on an axial raised rim. Based on valve outline and dimensions, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" box="[996,1137,848,873]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="quesadae">
<emphasis box="[996,1137,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">P. quesadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="borealis" variety="pseudolanceolata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">P. borealis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[303,510,887,912]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">pseudolanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the presence of the rim and the less radiate striation pattern should prevent misidentification (Table 1). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" box="[477,774,925,950]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="perlanceolata">
<emphasis box="[477,774,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Pinnularia perlanceolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has valves that are clearly wider (
<quantity box="[1171,1337,925,951]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.17" metricValueMax="1.28" metricValueMin="1.06" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" unit="mm" value="11.7" valueMax="12.8" valueMin="10.6">10.6–12.8 µm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.149999999999999" metricValueMax="9.6" metricValueMin="8.7" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" unit="mm" value="9.149999999999999" valueMax="9.6" valueMin="8.7">8.7– 9.6 µm</quantity>
) with a more elliptic-lanceolate valve outline, lower number of striae (5–6 vs. 
<quantity box="[1208,1284,964,990]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.651" metricValueMax="1.778" metricValueMin="1.524" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" unit="in" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[1294,1373,964,990]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Zidarova" authorityYear="2011" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="quesadae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">P. quesadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and an almost straight raphe with straight to weakly deflected central endings.
</paragraph>
